<br>
To sum up your post, you feel that VI should have a longer patch and expansion development and testing cycle.  On one hand I agree (less inital bugs and less subsequent patching).  On the other hand, I'm a f*cking EQ addict and I want more and I want it now!<br>
<br>
Obviously SOE and VI have a corporate structure and policy regarding these activities (patching, expansion development, and testing) and therein lies the problem.  If SOE gives, say, a 4 week lead-time for improvement patch development and 1 week for testing (and I'm just throwing numbers around here), that may simply not be enough time.  <br>
<br>
I'm sure we're ALL familiar about software development and release dates...the two just don't mix.  Same sh*t here.  They're probably still completing a patch during the alloted testing phase AND/OR fixing major bugs that creep up during testing.<br>
<br>
I totally agree with you on the &quot;doing it right the first time&quot; thing.  Why is it that companies never have time to do it right the first time yet always manage to allocate resources to fix it?<br>
<br>
<br>
Kurley Greenleaf<br>
